Demand description

R

I want to recreate this figure in form. This bar chart has gradient fills and looks visually appealing. Id like to see how experts reproduce it and learn how to implement it in R.

https://www.nature.com/articles/s41585-021-00442-8

4 | 25-44%19%PSA

Source: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41585-021-00442-8

Fig. 4 | The prevalence of metastatic prostate cancer in selected Asian countries, England and the USA. Except for Japan, many Asian countries have higher rates (2544%) of advanced-stage disease than the USA (19%). The widespread PSA screening programme in Japan has been associated with a significant decrease in national mortality rate during this time period.

Input Files

easy_input.csvthe prevalence of metastatic prostate cancerbar

easy_input.csv, the prevalence of metastatic prostate cancer. The first column corresponds to the x-axis in the figure, the second and third columns are the two parts of each bar in the figure, and the fourth column is the sum of the second and third columns.

# 
# Read data
df <- read.csv("easy_input.csv")

# 
# Get number of rows
maxID <- nrow(df)

# ID
# Add ID column for plotting
df$ID <- 1:maxID

Plotting

# 
# Reshape data to long format
plot.df.all <- reshape2::melt(df, id.var = c("Country", "ID"), value.name = "Percentage", variable.name = "Type")

# 
# Filter data types to plot
plot.df <- subset(plot.df.all,Type %in% c("Metastatic", "Localized"))

# Metastatic
# Extract Metastatic data for layer overlay and text annotation
plot.df1 <- subset(plot.df, Type == "Metastatic") 

###  ---------------
### Set fill colors ---------------

# 
# Gradient colors for first dataset
type.color.1 <- c('#dbeffc','#7bb8e5') 

# 
# Gradient colors for second dataset (lower part in figure, overlaying the first)
type.color.2 <- c('#a7d7f3','#0079bb')

Here we provide two approaches: horizontal gradient and radial gradient.

Option 1: Radial gradient

# 
# Bar width
barwidth <- 0.44 

plot1 <- ggplot() +
  # 
  # Plot first group
  geom_col_pattern(
    data = plot.df,
    mapping = aes(ID, Percentage),
    width = barwidth,
    position = "stack",
    pattern = 'gradient',
    pattern_orientation = "radial",
    pattern_fill = type.color.1[1], 
    pattern_fill2 = type.color.1[2], 
    fill = NA) + 
  
  # bar
  # Plot second group, overlaying the previous bars
  geom_col_pattern(
    data = plot.df1,
    mapping = aes(ID, Percentage),
    width = barwidth,
    pattern = 'gradient',
    pattern_orientation = "radial",
    pattern_fill = type.color.2[1], 
    pattern_fill2 = type.color.2[2], 
    fill = NA) + 
  
  # 
  # Add text
  geom_text(data = plot.df1, mapping = aes(x = ID, y = (Percentage/2), label = paste0(Percentage, " %")),
            size = 2.5, color = "white") + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1, maxID, 1), labels = stringr::str_wrap(plot.df1$Country, 9)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,100), breaks = seq(0, 100, 10), expand = c(0, 0)) +
  labs(x = "") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(aspect.ratio = 0.5) +
  theme(panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(), 
        panel.grid.minor.x = element_blank(), 
        panel.grid.minor.y = element_blank(), 
        legend.text = element_text(colour = 'black', size = 9),
        axis.text = element_text(colour = 'black', size = 9),
        axis.line = element_line(colour = 'black'),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"),
        panel.border = element_blank())
plot1

ggsave("bar_radial.pdf", width = 7, height = 5)

Option 2: Horizontal gradient

# 
# Bar width, plot left and right halves separately
barwidth <- 0.22 

plot2 <- ggplot() +
  # 
  # Fill left half
  geom_col_pattern(
    data = plot.df,
    mapping = aes( (ID-(barwidth/2)), Percentage),
    width = barwidth,
    position = "stack",
    pattern = 'gradient',
    pattern_orientation = "horizontal", 
    pattern_fill = type.color.1[2], 
    pattern_fill2 = type.color.1[1], 
    fill = NA) + 
  
  # 
  # Fill right half
  geom_col_pattern(
    data = plot.df,
    mapping = aes( (ID+(barwidth/2)), Percentage),
    width = barwidth,
    position = "stack",
    pattern = 'gradient',
    pattern_orientation = "horizontal", 
    pattern_fill = type.color.1[1], 
    pattern_fill2 = type.color.1[2], 
    fill = NA) + 
  
  # bar
  # Fill left half, overlay previous bars
  geom_col_pattern(
    data = plot.df1,
    mapping = aes( (ID-(barwidth/2)), Percentage),
    width = barwidth,
    pattern = 'gradient',
    pattern_orientation = "horizontal",
    pattern_fill = type.color.2[2], 
    pattern_fill2 = type.color.2[1], 
    fill = NA) + 
  # bar
  # Fill right half, overlay previous bars
  geom_col_pattern(
    data = plot.df1,
    mapping = aes( (ID+(barwidth/2)), Percentage),
    width = barwidth,
    pattern = 'gradient',
    pattern_orientation = "horizontal",
    pattern_fill = type.color.2[1], 
    pattern_fill2 = type.color.2[2],
    fill = NA) +
  
  # geom_rect 
  # Add black borders with geom_rect, can be commented out if not needed
  geom_rect(
    data = plot.df1,
    mapping = aes(xmin = ID - barwidth, xmax = ID + barwidth, ymin = 0, ymax = Percentage),
    size = 0.3,
    fill = NA,
    color = "black")+
  geom_rect(
    data = df,
    mapping = aes(xmin = ID-barwidth, xmax = ID + barwidth, 
                  ymin = Metastatic, 
                  ymax = Total),
    size = 0.3,
    fill = NA,
    color = "black") + 
  
  # 
  # Add text
  geom_text(data = plot.df1, mapping = aes(x = ID, y = (Percentage/2), label = paste0(Percentage, " %")),
            size = 2.5, color = "white") + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1, maxID, 1), labels = stringr::str_wrap(plot.df1$Country, 9)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,100), breaks = seq(0,100,10), expand = c(0,0)) +
  labs(x = "") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(aspect.ratio = 0.5) +
  theme(panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(), 
        panel.grid.minor.x = element_blank(), 
        panel.grid.minor.y = element_blank(), 
        legend.text = element_text(colour = 'black', size = 9),
        axis.text = element_text(colour = 'black', size = 9),
        axis.line = element_line(colour = 'black'),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"),
        panel.border = element_blank())
